Backup failures differ across protected workloads because each platform has its own dependency chain and recovery path. For example, an AHV backup failure may be caused by snapshot/checkpoint issues requiring virtualization team validation; an Oracle backup failure may involve RMAN, archive logs, mount points, or database state requiring DBA intervention; a SQL backup failure may depend on VSS writer health, SQL service availability, or database accessibility; and a File System (Windows/Linux) backup failure may relate to agent connectivity, permissions, mount paths, or host-level issues where an agent restart is not a reliable or complete resolution. For NAS workloads (NFS/Isilon), failures may stem from export access, snapshot locks, or storage-side conditions. Achieving any form of self-healing across these workloads would require integration with multiple technologies, platforms, and operational teams (virtualization, database, storage, OS), introducing significant complexity in scripting, validation, permissions, and dependency management. At the Cohesity cluster level, service faults, node issues, or hardware alerts also require operational review and internal/vendor consultation before any action, as cluster services and hardware states can impact the broader backup environment. Due to these workload-specific dependencies and cross-platform integration requirements, true self-healing is not practical at this stage. The current focus remains on operational automation to improve detection, validation, incident enrichment, and faster triage rather than automated remediation. Cohesity does provide platform resiliency features such as service failover, node failover, and cluster health monitoring; however, these support cluster stability and availability rather than end-to-end workload self-healing.
